revision.text:
The '''2016 Saudi Arabian snowstorm''' was an [[Extreme weather|extreme weather event]] in late November 2016, in which parts of the [[Arabian Desert|Arabian desert]] in [[Saudi Arabia]] experienced subzero temperatures, snowfall and flooding. 

Snow was first reported in northern parts of Saudi Arabia on 23 November. By 25 November, temperatures as low as {{convert|-4|C|F}} were reported in [[Turaif]], in [[Northern Borders Region]], and there was snow cover in central and northeastern regions.<ref name=AlA>{{cite news |author=Dhafer Al-Bakri |url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2016/11/27/Below-zero-Snow-covers-sand-in-some-Saudi-regions-.html |title=Below zero? Snow covers sand in Saudi regions |website=[[Al Arabiya English|Al Arabiya]] |date=27 November 2016 }}</ref><ref name=Watchers>{{cite web|website=The Watchers|url=http://watchers.news/2016/11/30/snow-flood-saudi-arabia-november-2016/|title=Saudi Arabia deserts covered in snow, followed by deadly floods|date=30 November 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Past Weather in Turaif, Saudi Arabia — November 2016|url=https://www.timeanddate.com/weather/saudi-arabia/turaif/historic?month=11&year=2016|website=timeanddate|accessdate=29 July 2017}}</ref> Normal seasonal temperatures do not fall below {{convert|20|C|F}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/2290544/frozen-deserts-shock-saudi-arabia-as-3-cold-snap-brings-blankets-of-snow/|title=Shiver and Sheikh: Frozen deserts shock Saudi Arabia as -3 cold snap brings blankets of snow |date=29 November 2016 |newspaper=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]] |location=UK |author=Jon Lockett}}</ref><ref name=AU>{{cite news |url=http://www.news.com.au/technology/environment/frozen-deserts-shock-saudi-arabia-as-3-cold-snap-brings-blankets-of-snow/news-story/07dc0fdd561cdc45292c6154416f104d |title=Frozen deserts shock Saudi Arabia as -3 cold snap brings blankets of snow |website=news.com.au |date=30 November 2016 }}</ref> Many Saudis enjoyed unusual outdoor activities such as building [[Snowman|snowmen]] and sliding;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/world/world-news/saudi-arabia-desert-kingdom-partially-covered-under-snow-with-extreme-temperature-drop-4402712/ |title=Parts of Saudi Arabia covered in snow, temperatures plunge |newspaper=[[The Indian Express]] |date=30 November 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Sofia Petkar |url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/11/29/it-snowed-in-saudi-arabia-and-everyone-had-a-great-time-6289381/ |title=It snowed in Saudi Arabia and everyone had a great time |newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |location=UK |date=29 November 2016 }}</ref><ref name=Star>{{cite news |author=Peter Truman |url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/latest-news/566531/weather-snow-saudi-arabia-snowmen-skating-arab |title=Freaky weather: Layer of SNOW covers DESERT and people don't know what to think |newspaper=[[Daily Star (British newspaper)|Daily Star]] |location=UK |date=1 December 2016 }}</ref> however, the snow was followed by rain and lightning that caused flooding and led to the deaths of at least 7 people.<ref name=Watchers/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2016/11/30/Heavy-rain-floods-in-Saudi-Arabia-leave-seven-dead.html |title=Heavy rain, floods in Saudi Arabia leave seven dead |newspaper=[[Saudi Gazette]] |via=''Al Arabiya English'' |date=30 November 2016 }}</ref>

{{As of|2016|12|22}}, snow had also fallen in [[Israel]], [[Syria]] and other parts of the [[Middle East]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/worldnews/9793865/Snow-blankets-parts-of-Israel-Syria-and-the-Middle-East.html?frame=2448489&amgpage=1 |title=Snow blankets parts of Israel, Syria and the Middle East |newspaper=[[Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |location=UK |date=22 December 2016 |type=slideshow }}</ref>

Snow has occasionally occurred in Saudi Arabia in previous winters. In 2013 a video of a man somersaulting in snow there circulated on [[social media]].<ref name=AU/> In January 2015 a cleric issued a [[fatwa]] against building snowmen.<ref name=Star/> In January 2016, snow fell between [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]] for the first time in 85 years.<ref name=Watchers/>

